    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2815812198" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2815812198" />
    <a title="Jackie Jameson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8718207-jackie-jameson"><img alt="Jackie Jameson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1344558405p2/8718207.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2815812198?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jackie Jameson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jackie Jameson" href="/user/show/8718207-jackie-jameson">Jackie Jameson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2815812198" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17753511380955641104">Minnette Walters has really a talent for taking the traditional English murder mystery and then twisting the shit out of it into some bizarre dynamic you didn’t see coming. “The Scold’s Bridle” is one such book. Ultimately creepy, incest riddled murder mystery. I would give the advice to a reader to pay really good attention to the excerpts from the murdered woman’s diaries that are throughout the book. They are truly integral in understanding the complete brilliance that comes at the ending. Ju</span>
  <span id="freeText17753511380955641104" style="display:none">Minnette Walters has really a talent for taking the traditional English murder mystery and then twisting the shit out of it into some bizarre dynamic you didn’t see coming. “The Scold’s Bridle” is one such book. Ultimately creepy, incest riddled murder mystery. I would give the advice to a reader to pay really good attention to the excerpts from the murdered woman’s diaries that are throughout the book. They are truly integral in understanding the complete brilliance that comes at the ending. Just a marvelous read from one of my favorite authors.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17753511380955641104" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


