  <span id="freeText489840430260510795" style="display:none">trigger warning<br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[incest<br />rape<br />gang rape<br />domestic abuse<br />child abuse<br />suicide and belittling of suicide<br />torture <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />An old woman is found with slitted wrists in her bathtub, wearing a Scold's Bridle and having sleeping pills in her system. Suicide is quickly ruled out for various reasons, well, but who's done it?<br /><br />I understand that thos book is aging and that the author herself isn't the youngest and has been raised in a different world than the one I am living in. I still find it wrong to state again and again that suicide is a way only a coward chooses, or to let a character state it without commenting further by way of narration.<br />It is harmfull, especially if a book is as popular as this one seems to be.<br /><br />I am pissed. Or would be, if I were able to have emotions at the moment. <br />Because you know what? I am one of these persons who grew up with violence and suffer for it for the rest of their lives. Not a plot device but a breathing human being.<br /><br />I like how it is depicted that if you react with violence to violence, you're creating a spiral that touches everyone in the near vicinity, because it's true. But that's only a small part of this bulk of misery.</span>
